68":"1568","1534":"1534","1600":"1600","1445":"1445","1488":"1488","1486":"1486","1509":"1509","1508":"1508","Durham, England":"Durham, England","Stowmarket, Suffolk, England":"Stowmarket, Suffolk, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","Cresswell, Northumberland, England":"Cresswell, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Creswell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places called Cresswell, in Derbyshire, Staffordshire, and Northumberland, or from various other places also named with Old English <i>cærse</i> ‘cress’ + <i>wiella</i> ‘stream’, including Carswell (Berkshire and Devon), Caswell (Dorset, Northamptonshire, and Somerset), Crasswall (Herefordshire), Kerswell (Devon and Worcestershire), or Kerswill (Devon). See also   Caswell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Caswell","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places in Dorset, Northamptonshire, and Somerset named Caswell, from Old English <i>cærse</i> ‘(water)cress’ + <i>well(a)</i> ‘spring, stream’. See also   Creswell  ."]},{"name":"Carswell","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Creswell  ."]},{"name":"Chriswell","meanings":["English: probably a variant of <b>Criswell</b>, itself a variant of   Creswell  ."]},{"name":"Cresswell","meanings":["English: variant of   Creswell  ."]},{"name":"Criswell","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire): variant of   Creswell  ."]},{"name":"Croswell","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Creswell  . This may also be a habitational name from an unidentified place in Shropshire or Berkshire."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Creswell of Cresswell was born in 1486, in Cresswell, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom as the son of George Cresswell of Cresswell. He married Elizabeth Lumley in 1508, in Durham, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1534, in Stowmarket, Suffolk, England, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1486–1534":"1486–1534","–Male":"Surnud","1488–1547":"1488–1547","1508–1600":"1508–1600","–1568":"–1568","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1547":"1547","1568":"1568","1534":"1534","1600":"1600","1445":"1445","1488":"1488","1486":"1486","1509":"1509","1508":"1508","Durham, England":"Durham, England","Stowmarket, Suffolk, England":"Stowmarket, Suffolk, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","Cresswell, Northumberland, England":"Cresswell, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1486–1534":"1486–1534","–Male":"Kuollut","1488–1547":"1488–1547","1508–1600":"1508–1600","–1568":"–1568","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1547":"1547","1568":"1568","1534":"1534","1600":"1600","1445":"1445","1488":"1488","1486":"1486","1509":"1509","1508":"1508","Durham, England":"Durham, England","Stowmarket, Suffolk, England":"Stowmarket, Suffolk, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","Cresswell, Northumberland, England